Detailed Description

Objects derived from this class are used to describe a type of data that can be used in a data description.

Note: When implementing the abstract methods of this class, in general data from Python can be trusted as it has been through the 'isSameType' check, but data from sections and streams cannot and must always be checked for errors.

virtual bool DataType::addToSection ( PyObject *  pValue,
DataSectionPtr  pSection 
) const [pure virtual]

This method adds the value of the appropriate type into the input data section.

The value can be assumed to have been created by this class or to have (previously) passed the isSameType check.

Parameters:
pValue The value to add.
pSection The data section to add the value to.
Returns:
true if succeeded, false otherwise. In the failure case, the section is generally clobbered, and should be discarded.

This method adds the value of the appropriate type onto the input bundle.

The value can be assumed to have been created by this class or to have (previously) passed the isSameType check. If isPersistentOnly is true, then the object should streamed only the persistent parts of itself.

Parameters:

stream The stream to add the value to.
isPersistentOnly Indicates if only persistent data is being added.
Returns:
true if succeeded, false otherwise. In the failure case, the stream is generally clobbered and should be discarded.

PropertyOwnerBase * DataType::asOwner ( PyObject *  pObject  )  [virtual]

This method returns the given object, which was created by us, in the form of a PropertyOwnerBase, i.e.

an object which can own other objects. If the object cannot own other objects, then NULL should be returned.

This base class implementation always returns NULL.

Reimplemented in ArrayDataType, ClassDataType, and FixedDictDataType.

PyObjectPtr DataType::attach ( PyObject *  pObject,
PropertyOwnerBase *  pOwner,
int  ownerRef 
) [virtual]

This method first checks the type of the given object.

If it fails, then it returns NULL. If it succeeds then it tells the object who its owner is, if it needs to know (i.e. if it is mutable and needs to tell its owner when it is modified). This base class implementation assumes that the object is const. Finally it returns a pointer to the same object passed in. Some implementations will need to copy the object if it already has another owner. In this case the newly-created object is returned instead.

Reimplemented in ArrayDataType, ClassDataType, and FixedDictDataType.
